name: dataproc
title: Google Cloud Dataproc API
description: Manages Hadoop-based clusters and jobs on Google Cloud Platform.

parameters.name: prettyPrint
parameters.desc: Returns response with indentations and line breaks.

parameters.name: key
parameters.desc: API key. Your API key identifies your project and provides you with API access, quota, and reports. Required unless you provide an OAuth 2.0 token.

parameters.name: quotaUser
parameters.desc: Available to use for quota purposes for server-side applications. Can be any arbitrary string assigned to a user, but should not exceed 40 characters.

parameters.name: oauth_token
parameters.desc: OAuth 2.0 token for the current user.

parameters.name: fields
parameters.desc: Selector specifying which fields to include in a partial response.

schemas.name: ListClustersResponse
schemas.desc: The list of all clusters in a project.

fields.name: clusters
fields.desc: Output-only The clusters in the project.

fields.name: nextPageToken
fields.desc: Output-only This token is included in the response if there are more results to fetch. To fetch additional results, provide this value as the page_token in a subsequent ListClustersRequest.

schemas.name: HadoopJob
schemas.desc: A Cloud Dataproc job for running Apache Hadoop MapReduce (https://hadoop.apache.org/docs/current/hadoop-mapreduce-client/hadoop-mapreduce-client-core/MapReduceTutorial.html) jobs on Apache Hadoop YARN (https://hadoop.apache.org/docs/r2.7.1/hadoop-yarn/hadoop-yarn-site/YARN.html).

fields.name: jarFileUris
fields.desc: Optional Jar file URIs to add to the CLASSPATHs of the Hadoop driver and tasks.

fields.name: loggingConfig
fields.desc: Optional The runtime log config for job execution.

fields.name: properties
fields.desc: Optional A mapping of property names to values, used to configure Hadoop. Properties that conflict with values set by the Cloud Dataproc API may be overwritten. Can include properties set in /etc/hadoop/conf/*-site and classes in user code.

fields.name: args
fields.desc: Optional The arguments to pass to the driver. Do not include arguments, such as -libjars or -Dfoo=bar, that can be set as job properties, since a collision may occur that causes an incorrect job submission.

fields.name: fileUris
fields.desc: Optional HCFS (Hadoop Compatible Filesystem) URIs of files to be copied to the working directory of Hadoop drivers and distributed tasks. Useful for naively parallel tasks.

fields.name: mainClass
fields.desc: The name of the driver's main class. The jar file containing the class must be in the default CLASSPATH or specified in jar_file_uris.

fields.name: archiveUris
fields.desc: Optional HCFS URIs of archives to be extracted in the working directory of Hadoop drivers and tasks. Supported file types: .jar, .tar, .tar.gz, .tgz, or .zip.

fields.name: mainJarFileUri
fields.desc: The HCFS URI of the jar file containing the main class. Examples:  'gs://foo-bucket/analytics-binaries/extract-useful-metrics-mr.jar'  'hdfs:/tmp/test-samples/custom-wordcount.jar'  'file:///home/usr/lib/hadoop-mapreduce/hadoop-mapreduce-examples.jar'

schemas.name: LoggingConfig
schemas.desc: The runtime logging config of the job.

fields.name: driverLogLevels
fields.desc: The per-package log levels for the driver. This may include "root" package name to configure rootLogger. Examples:  'com.google = FATAL', 'root = INFO', 'org.apache = DEBUG'

schemas.name: InstanceGroupConfig
schemas.desc: Optional The config settings for Google Compute Engine resources in an instance group, such as a master or worker group.

fields.name: imageUri
fields.desc: Output-only The Google Compute Engine image resource used for cluster instances. Inferred from SoftwareConfig.image_version.

fields.name: instanceNames
fields.desc: Optional The list of instance names. Cloud Dataproc derives the names from cluster_name, num_instances, and the instance group if not set by user (recommended practice is to let Cloud Dataproc derive the name).

fields.name: accelerators
fields.desc: Optional The Google Compute Engine accelerator configuration for these instances.Beta Feature: This feature is still under development. It may be changed before final release.

fields.name: numInstances
fields.desc: Required The number of VM instances in the instance group. For master instance groups, must be set to 1.

fields.name: diskConfig
fields.desc: Optional Disk option config settings.

fields.name: isPreemptible
fields.desc: Optional Specifies that this instance group contains preemptible instances.

fields.name: managedGroupConfig
fields.desc: Output-only The config for Google Compute Engine Instance Group Manager that manages this group. This is only used for preemptible instance groups.

fields.name: machineTypeUri
fields.desc: Required The Google Compute Engine machine type used for cluster instances. Example: https://www.googleapis.com/compute/v1/projects/[project_id]/zones/us-east1-a/machineTypes/n1-standard-2.

enum.name: CREATING
enum.desc: The cluster is being created and set up. It is not ready for use.

enum.name: RUNNING
enum.desc: The cluster is currently running and healthy. It is ready for use.

enum.name: ERROR
enum.desc: The cluster encountered an error. It is not ready for use.

enum.name: DELETING
enum.desc: The cluster is being deleted. It cannot be used.

enum.name: UPDATING
enum.desc: The cluster is being updated. It continues to accept and process jobs.

fields.desc: Optional Maximum number of times per hour a driver may be restarted as a result of driver terminating with non-zero code before job is reported failed.A job may be reported as thrashing if driver exits with non-zero code 4 times within 10 minute window.Maximum value is 10.

schemas.name: Status
schemas.desc:
The Status type defines a logical error model that is suitable for different programming environments, including REST APIs and RPC APIs. It is used by gRPC (https://github.com/grpc). The error model is designed to be:
Simple to use and understand for most users
Flexible enough to meet unexpected needsOverviewThe Status message contains three pieces of data: error code, error message, and error details. The error code should be an enum value of google.rpc.Code, but it may accept additional error codes if needed. The error message should be a developer-facing English message that helps developers understand and resolve the error. If a localized user-facing error message is needed, put the localized message in the error details or localize it in the client. The optional error details may contain arbitrary information about the error. There is a predefined set of error detail types in the package google.rpc which can be used for common error conditions.Language mappingThe Status message is the logical representation of the error model, but it is not necessarily the actual wire format. When the Status message is exposed in different client libraries and different wire protocols, it can be mapped differently. For example, it will likely be mapped to some exceptions in Java, but more likely mapped to some error codes in C.Other usesThe error model and the Status message can be used in a variety of environments, either with or without APIs, to provide a consistent developer experience across different environments.Example uses of this error model include:
Partial errors. If a service needs to return partial errors to the client, it may embed the Status in the normal response to indicate the partial errors.
Workflow errors. A typical workflow has multiple steps. Each step may have a Status message for error reporting purpose.
Batch operations. If a client uses batch request and batch response, the Status message should be used directly inside batch response, one for each error sub-response.
Asynchronous operations. If an API call embeds asynchronous operation results in its response, the status of those operations should be represented directly using the Status message.
Logging. If some API errors are stored in logs, the message Status could be used directly after any stripping needed for security/privacy reasons.

fields.name: details
fields.desc: A list of messages that carry the error details. There will be a common set of message types for APIs to use.

fields.name: code
fields.desc: The status code, which should be an enum value of google.rpc.Code.

fields.name: message
fields.desc: A developer-facing error message, which should be in English. Any user-facing error message should be localized and sent in the google.rpc.Status.details field, or localized by the client.

schemas.name: DiskConfig
schemas.desc: Specifies the config of disk options for a group of VM instances.

fields.name: numLocalSsds
fields.desc: Optional Number of attached SSDs, from 0 to 4 (default is 0). If SSDs are not attached, the boot disk is used to store runtime logs and HDFS (https://hadoop.apache.org/docs/r1.2.1/hdfs_user_guide.html) data. If one or more SSDs are attached, this runtime bulk data is spread across them, and the boot disk contains only basic config and installed binaries.

fields.name: bootDiskSizeGb
fields.desc: Optional Size in GB of the boot disk (default is 500GB).

schemas.name: ClusterConfig
schemas.desc: The cluster config.

fields.name: gceClusterConfig
fields.desc: Required The shared Google Compute Engine config settings for all instances in a cluster.

fields.name: softwareConfig
fields.desc: Optional The config settings for software inside the cluster.

fields.name: masterConfig
fields.desc: Optional The Google Compute Engine config settings for the master instance in a cluster.

fields.name: secondaryWorkerConfig
fields.desc: Optional The Google Compute Engine config settings for additional worker instances in a cluster.

fields.name: initializationActions
fields.desc: Optional Commands to execute on each node after config is completed. By default, executables are run on master and all worker nodes. You can test a node's role metadata to run an executable on a master or worker node, as shown below using curl (you can also use wget): ROLE=$(curl -H Metadata-Flavor:Google http://metadata/computeMetadata/v1/instance/attributes/dataproc-role) if [[ "${ROLE}" == 'Master' ]]; then ... master specific actions ... else ... worker specific actions ... fi

fields.name: configBucket
fields.desc: Optional A Google Cloud Storage staging bucket used for sharing generated SSH keys and config. If you do not specify a staging bucket, Cloud Dataproc will determine an appropriate Cloud Storage location (US, ASIA, or EU) for your cluster's staging bucket according to the Google Compute Engine zone where your cluster is deployed, and then it will create and manage this project-level, per-location bucket for you.

fields.name: workerConfig
fields.desc: Optional The Google Compute Engine config settings for worker instances in a cluster.

The ID must contain only letters (a-z, A-Z), numbers (0-9), underscores (_), or hyphens (-). The maximum length is 100 characters.

schemas.name: JobStatus
schemas.desc: Cloud Dataproc job status.

fields.name: state
fields.desc: Output-only A state message specifying the overall job state.

enum.name: PENDING
enum.desc: The job is pending; it has been submitted, but is not yet running.

enum.name: SETUP_DONE
enum.desc: Job has been received by the service and completed initial setup; it will soon be submitted to the cluster.

enum.name: RUNNING
enum.desc: The job is running on the cluster.

enum.name: CANCEL_PENDING
enum.desc: A CancelJob request has been received, but is pending.

enum.name: CANCEL_STARTED
enum.desc: Transient in-flight resources have been canceled, and the request to cancel the running job has been issued to the cluster.

enum.name: ERROR
enum.desc: The job has completed, but encountered an error.

enum.name: ATTEMPT_FAILURE
enum.desc: Job attempt has failed. The detail field contains failure details for this attempt.Applies to restartable jobs only.

fields.name: details
fields.desc: Output-only Optional job state details, such as an error description if the state is ERROR.

fields.desc: Optional The Google Compute Engine subnetwork to be used for machine communications. Cannot be specified with network_uri. Example: https://www.googleapis.com/compute/v1/projects/[project_id]/regions/us-east1/sub0.

fields.name: networkUri
fields.desc: Optional The Google Compute Engine network to be used for machine communications. Cannot be specified with subnetwork_uri. If neither network_uri nor subnetwork_uri is specified, the "default" network of the project is used, if it exists. Cannot be a "Custom Subnet Network" (see Using Subnetworks for more information). Example: https://www.googleapis.com/compute/v1/projects/[project_id]/regions/global/default.

fields.name: zoneUri
fields.desc: Required The zone where the Google Compute Engine cluster will be located. Example: https://www.googleapis.com/compute/v1/projects/[project_id]/zones/[zone].

fields.name: metadata
fields.desc: The Google Compute Engine metadata entries to add to all instances (see Project and instance metadata (https://cloud.google.com/compute/docs/storing-retrieving-metadata#project_and_instance_metadata)).

fields.name: internalIpOnly
fields.desc: Optional If true, all instances in the cluster will only have internal IP addresses. By default, clusters are not restricted to internal IP addresses, and will have ephemeral external IP addresses assigned to each instance. This internal_ip_only restriction can only be enabled for subnetwork enabled networks, and all off-cluster dependencies must be configured to be accessible without external IP addresses.

fields.name: serviceAccountScopes
fields.desc:
Optional The URIs of service account scopes to be included in Google Compute Engine instances. The following base set of scopes is always included:
https://www.googleapis.com/auth/cloud.useraccounts.readonly
https://www.googleapis.com/auth/devstorage.read_write
https://www.googleapis.com/auth/logging.writeIf no scopes are specified, the following defaults are also provided:
https://www.googleapis.com/auth/bigquery
https://www.googleapis.com/auth/bigtable.admin.table
https://www.googleapis.com/auth/bigtable.data
https://www.googleapis.com/auth/devstorage.full_control

fields.name: tags
fields.desc: The Google Compute Engine tags to add to all instances (see Tagging instances).

fields.name: done
fields.desc: If the value is false, it means the operation is still in progress. If true, the operation is completed, and either error or response is available.

fields.name: response
fields.desc: The normal response of the operation in case of success. If the original method returns no data on success, such as Delete, the response is google.protobuf.Empty. If the original method is standard Get/Create/Update, the response should be the resource. For other methods, the response should have the type XxxResponse, where Xxx is the original method name. For example, if the original method name is TakeSnapshot(), the inferred response type is TakeSnapshotResponse.

fields.name: name
fields.desc: The server-assigned name, which is only unique within the same service that originally returns it. If you use the default HTTP mapping, the name should have the format of operations/some/unique/name.

fields.name: error
fields.desc: The error result of the operation in case of failure or cancellation.

fields.name: metadata
fields.desc: Service-specific metadata associated with the operation. It typically contains progress information and common metadata such as create time. Some services might not provide such metadata. Any method that returns a long-running operation should document the metadata type, if any.
